I bought a silver spoon this weekend. The seller says it is plate, but
I'm pretty sure it's sterling. It is about 12 inches long, and its
lines are very simple. Made by Gorham, it has the following
inscription:

Rochambeau
to Lt. Gov. Jabez Bowen
R.I.
1780

All I can find is that &quot;Rochambeau&quot; is Jean Baptiste Donatien de Vimeur,
comte de Rochambeau
(1725-1807), Commander-in-chief of the French forces during the American
Revolution. He was instrumental in the Battle of Worktown, the deciding
battler of the RW. He quartered troops in Rhode Island in 1780-81. I
can't find any reference at all on the 'net to J. Bowen (Lt. Gov's don't
seem to matter much in history).

I have yet to contact Gorham but will try; any commemorative silver or
Rev. War buffs here who can help? Any ideas on what value might be, or
which group might be interested in having it (lilke someone in
Williamsburg, etc.)?

Please reply to group as this is an employer-provided account. Thanks

